# DNS Redirect Loop Fix

Source: [ChatGPT conversation](https://chatgpt.com/c/680308e7-d364-8006-8d2e-484361ef1791)

## Assistant

TeleHack is a lovingly crafted emulation of the pre‑Internet era—complete with Usenet, FTP, gopher, and its own BBS “phonebook.” Here’s how to jump back in and rebuild your rolodex from scratch:

1. Connect to TeleHack

You can use any telnet client, or even your browser:

Via Telnet (CLI)

Bash
telnet telehack.com 23

Via Web
Go to https://telehack.com/
 and click “Connect” (it’ll launch a JavaScript-based terminal).

When you connect, you’ll see a login prompt. Just press Enter at the “Username:” prompt and then again at “Password:” to enter as a guest.

2. Explore the Phonebook

Once you’re in, TeleHack gives you a virtual phonebook—an address index of all its simulated BBSes and services.

View the current phonebook:

Shell
phonebook

Search for an entry:

Shell
phonebook FIND keyword

See help for phonebook commands:

Shell
help phonebook
3. Building Your Own Phonebook

TeleHack’s “phonebook” is actually a text file you can edit. Here’s a typical workflow:

Switch to the “net” directory (where the phonebook lives):

Shell
cd /net

List files (you should see phonebook):

Shell
ls -l

Edit the phonebook with the built‑in editor (called ed‑style):

Shell
changes phonebook

Add entries in the format:

BBS_NAME   1234   /path/to/bbs

For example:

RETROCHAT   4321   /bbs/retrochat
OLDTIMES    8675   /bbs/oldtimes

Save & quit the editor—just follow the on‑screen prompts (type E to exit, etc.).

4. Making It Persistent

By default, TeleHack is a shared, ephemeral system. If you want your phonebook edits to stick across sessions:

Register for an account:

Shell
register YOURNAME

Follow the prompts to choose a password.

Upload your phonebook to your home directory:

Shell
mkdir ~/myphonebook
cp /net/phonebook ~/myphonebook/phonebook.txt

You can then re‑import it each session:

Shell
cp ~/myphonebook/phonebook.txt /net/phonebook
5. Bonus Retro Fun

Gopher around:

Shell
gopher telehack.com

Play old‑school games: use ftp or tn3270 to connect to vintage game zines.

Check Usenet:

Shell
news newshost.telehack.com
TL;DR

Connect: telnet telehack.com or via the web client.

View/Edit: phonebook, then cd /net && changes phonebook to add your own.

Persist: register an account and store a private copy under ~/.

Have fun hacking the retro‑net and rebuilding your phonebook exactly the way you remember it!

## User

What is CDN/FQDN?

## Assistant

Here’s a quick breakdown of CDN and FQDN:

1. CDN (Content Delivery Network)

A CDN is a network of geographically distributed servers that work together to deliver content (like images, videos, or web pages) to users as quickly and efficiently as possible. The main goal is to reduce latency (the delay before a transfer of data begins) by serving content from a server that is physically closer to the user. This ensures faster loading times, less strain on the origin server, and improves overall user experience.

How it works:

Caching: CDNs store copies of static content (like images, CSS files, JavaScript, etc.) at various locations around the world.

Geographic proximity: When a user accesses a website, the CDN routes their request to the nearest server, which is more likely to have a cached copy of the content, speeding up delivery.

Load balancing: Distributes traffic across multiple servers to prevent overloads and ensure consistent performance.

Common examples:

Cloudflare

Akamai

Amazon CloudFront

Fastly

Benefits:

Faster load times

Reduced latency

Reduced bandwidth costs for origin servers

Improved site reliability and uptime

2. FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name)

An FQDN is the complete and specific domain name for a host on the internet. It uniquely identifies a machine or service in the domain name system (DNS) hierarchy.

An FQDN is composed of:

Host name – The specific machine or service within a domain (e.g., www).

Domain name – The name of the domain (e.g., example.com).

Top-level domain (TLD) – The suffix (e.g., .com, .org, .net).

Example:

FQDN: www.example.com.

www is the host (the specific machine or service, like a web server).

example is the domain name.

com is the TLD (top-level domain).

The final period (.) signifies the root of the DNS system (optional but understood).

Why it's important:

The FQDN ensures that the name is globally unique and resolves correctly in DNS.

Without the FQDN, DNS servers wouldn’t know how to fully resolve the address to the correct server.

TL;DR:

CDN: A network of servers that deliver content faster to users based on their location.

FQDN: A complete domain name that specifies the exact location of a server or service in the DNS hierarchy.

